abbalists’ shamanic practices, Garb compares their experiences with those of mystics from other traditions as well as with those recorded by psychologists such as Milton Erickson and Carl Jung. Finally, Garb examines the kabbalists’ relations with the wider Jewish community, uncovering the role of kabbalistic shamanism in the renewal of Jewish tradition as it contended with modernity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCabala. 0aShamanism. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  ajewish thought, judaism, religion, religious studies, faith, mysticism, history, historical, social sciences, comparative religions, kabbalists, psychological, psychology, consciousness, study, ritual, mental methods, trance states, heavenly mountains, cabala, shamanism, transformation, milton erickson, carl jung, modernity, empowerment, shamanic hasidism, hasidic trances.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022628207740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226282060423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226282060/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles